{{About|the literary concept||Resistance (disambiguation){{!}}Resistance}}
'''Resistance''' is a mythical concept created by [[United States|American]] novelist [[Steven Pressfield]] that illustrates the universal force that he claims acts against human [[creativity]].{{sfn|Holiday|2012}} It was first described in his non-fiction book ''[[The War of Art (book)|The War of Art]]''{{sfn|Pressfield|2002}} and elaborated in the follow-up books ''[[Do The Work]]''{{sfn|Pressfield|2011a}} and ''Turning Pro'',{{sfn|Pressfield|2012}} and in other essays.<ref>For example, {{harvnb|Pressfield|2011b}}.</ref> It is also a recurring theme in some of his fiction novels such as ''[[The Legend of Bagger Vance]]''{{sfn|Pressfield|1995}} and ''[[The Virtues of War]]''.{{sfn|Pressfield|2004}}

Resistance is described in a [[mythical]] fashion as a universal force that has one sole mission: to keep things as they are. Pressfield claims that Resistance does not have a personal vendetta against anyone, rather it is simply trying to accomplish its only mission.{{sfn|Pressfield|2002|p=11}} It is the force that will stop an individual's creative activity through any means necessary, whether it be [[Rationalization (psychology)|rationalizing]], inspiring [[fear]] and [[anxiety]], emphasizing other [[distraction]]s that require attention, raising the voice of an [[inner critic]], and much more. It will use any tool to stop creation flowing from an individual, no matter what field the creation is in.{{sfn|Pressfield|2002|pp=4–56}}

Pressfield goes on to claim that Resistance is the most dangerous element to one's life and dreams since its sole mission is to [[sabotage]] aspirations. He explains steps that human beings can take to overcome this force and keep it subdued so that they can create to their fullest potential, although Resistance is never fully gone.{{sfn|Pressfield|2012|p=74}}

Pressfield's concept of Resistance has been cited by authors such as [[Seth Godin]],{{sfn|Godin|2010}} [[David Kadavy]], [[David M. Kelley]] and Tom Kelley,{{sfn|Kelley|Kelley|2013}} [[Eric Liu]] and the [[Lincoln Center Institute]],{{sfn|Liu|Noppe-Brandon|2009}} [[Robert Kiyosaki]] and [[Sharon Lechter]],{{sfn|Kiyosaki|Lechter|2005}} and [[Gina Trapani]].{{sfn|Trapani|2008}}

==Criticism==
Psychologist Frederick Heide has cited Pressfield's book ''[[The War of Art (book)|The War of Art]]'' and questioned whether "fighting" Resistance is always a helpful metaphor; Heide suggested that such [[Agonistic behaviour|agonistic]] metaphors could end up "ironically perpetuating the resistance it predicts."{{sfn|Heide|2010|p=68}} Nevertheless, Heide noted, such an agonistic approach to resistance remains widespread in [[psychotherapeutic]] thinking.{{sfn|Heide|2010|p=79}} Heide cites a scholarly article that points to some alternative nonagonistic strategies for working with resistance in [[Relational psychoanalysis|relational psychoanalytic]] psychotherapy, [[Personal construct theory|personal construct]] therapy, [[narrative therapy]], [[motivational interviewing]], [[process-experiential therapy]], and [[coherence therapy]].{{sfn|Frankel|Levitt|2006|pp=220–221}}

